<p><a id=3D"definition" name=3D"Definition"></a></p>
<h2>What is the Area of Parallelogram?</h2>
<p>The <strong>area of a parallelogram</strong> is the region bounded by th=
e parallelogram in a given two-dimension space. To recall, a parallelogram =
is a special type of quadrilateral having the pair of opposite sides are pa=
rallel. In a parallelogram, the opposite sides are of equal length and oppo=
site angles are of equal measures.</p>
<p><img class=3D"aligncenter" title=3D"Area of a Parallelogram" src=3D"http=
s://cdn1.byjus.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/Area-of-Parallelogram-1.png" =
alt=3D"Area of a Parallelogram" width=3D"750" height=3D"403"><br>
<a id=3D"formula" name=3D"Formula"></a></p>
<h2>Area of Parallelogram Formula</h2>
<p align=3D"justify">To find the area of the parallelogram, multiply the ba=
se of the perpendicular by its height. It should be noted that the base and=
 the height of the parallelogram are perpendicular to each other, whereas t=
he lateral side of the parallelogram is not perpendicular to the base. Thus=
, a dotted line is drawn to represent the height.</p>
<p><img loading=3D"lazy" class=3D"aligncenter wp-image-4942 size-full" titl=
e=3D"Area of Parallelogram Formula" src=3D"https://cdn1.byjus.com/wp-conten=
t/uploads/2020/01/Area-of-Parallelogram-2.png" alt=3D"Area of Parallelogram=
 Formula" width=3D"750" height=3D"403"></p>
<p>Therefore,</p>
<table>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td style=3D"text-align: center;" align=3D"center"><strong>Area =3D b =C3=
=97 h Square units </strong></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p>Where =E2=80=9Cb=E2=80=9D is the base and =E2=80=9Ch=E2=80=9D is the hei=
ght of the parallelogram.</p>
<p>Let us learn the derivation of the area of a parallelogram, in the next =
section.</p>
<p><a id=3D"how-to-calculate" name=3D"How to Calculate"></a></p>
<h2>How to Calculate the Area of Parallelogram?</h2>
<p align=3D"justify">The parallelogram area can be calculated using its bas=
e and height. Apart from it, the area of a parallelogram can also be evalua=
ted if its two diagonals are known along with any of their intersecting ang=
les or if the length of the parallel sides is known, along with any of the =
angles between the sides. Hence, there are three methods to derive the area=
 of a parallelogram:</p>
<ul>
<li>When base and height of the parallelogram are given</li>
<li>When height is not given</li>
<li>When diagonals are given</li>
</ul>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><img loading=3D"lazy" class=3D"aligncenter wp-image-1107163 size-medium"=
 title=3D"How to Calculate the Area of Parallelograms?" src=3D"https://cdn1=
.byjus.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/Area-of-Parallelogram-3.png" alt=3D"H=
ow to Calculate the Area of Parallelograms?" width=3D"750" height=3D"403"><=
/p>
<p><a id=3D"using-sides" name=3D"Using Sides"></a></p>
<h3>Area of Parallelogram Using Sides</h3>
<p>Suppose a and b are the set of parallel sides of a parallelogram and h i=
s the height, then based on the length of sides and height of it, the formu=
la for its area is given by:</p>
<p>Area =3D Base&nbsp;=C3=97 Height</p>
<p><strong>A =3D b&nbsp;=C3=97 h&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;[sq.unit]</strong></p>
<p><strong>Example:</strong> If the base of a parallelogram is equal to 5 c=
m and the height is 3 cm, then find its area.</p>
<p>Solution: Given, the length of base=3D5 cm and height =3D 3 cm</p>
<p>As per the formula, Area =3D 5&nbsp;=C3=97 3 =3D 15 sq.cm<br>
<a id=3D"without-height" name=3D"Without Height"></a></p>
<h3>Area of Parallelogram Without Height</h3>
<p>If the height of the parallelogram is unknown to us, then we can use the=
 trigonometry concept here to find its area.</p>
<p><strong>Area =3D ab sin (x)</strong></p>
<p>Where a and b are the length of adjacent sides of the parallelogram and =
x is the angle between the sides of the parallelogram.</p>
<p><strong>Example: The angle between any two sides of a parallelogram is 9=
0 degrees. If the length of the two adjacent sides are 3 cm and 4 cm, respe=
ctively, then find the area.</strong></p>
<p>Solution: Let a =3D 3 cm and b=3D4 cm</p>
<p>x =3D 90 degrees</p>
<p>Area =3D ab&nbsp;sin (x)</p>
<p>A =3D 3&nbsp;=C3=97 4 sin (90)</p>
<p>A =3D 12 sin 90</p>
<p>A =3D 12&nbsp;=C3=97 1 =3D 12 sq.cm.</p>
<p><strong>Note:</strong> If the angle between the sides of a parallelogram=
 is 90 degrees, then it is a rectangle.<br>
<a id=3D"using-diagonals" name=3D"Using Diagonals"></a></p>
<h3>Area of Parallelogram Using Diagonals</h3>
<p>The area of any parallelogram can also be calculated using its diagonal =
lengths. As we know, there are two diagonals for a parallelogram, which int=
ersect each other. Suppose the diagonals intersect each other at an angle y=
, then the area of the parallelogram is given by:</p>
<p><strong>Area&nbsp;=3D =C2=BD =C3=97 d<sub>1</sub> =C3=97 d<sub>2</sub> s=
in (y)</strong></p>
<p>Check the table below to get summarised formulas of an area of a paralle=
logram.</p>
<table class=3D"table table-bordered">
<thead>
<tr>
<th colspan=3D"2">All Formulas to Calculate Area of a Parallelogram</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Using Base and Height</td>
<td>A =3D b =C3=97 h</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Using Trigonometry</td>
<td>A =3D ab sin (x)</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Using Diagonals</td>
<td>A =3D =C2=BD =C3=97 d<sub>1</sub> =C3=97 d<sub>2</sub> sin (y)</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p>Where,</p>
<ul>
<li>b =3D base of the parallelogram (AB)</li>
<li>h =3D height of the parallelogram</li>
<li>a =3D side of the parallelogram (AD)</li>
<li>x =3D any angle between the sides of the parallelogram (=E2=88=A0DAB or=
 =E2=88=A0ADC)</li>
<li>d<sub>1</sub> =3D diagonal of the parallelogram (p)</li>
<li>d<sub>2</sub> =3D diagonal of the parallelogram (q)</li>
<li>y =3D any angle between at the intersection point of the diagonals (=E2=
=88=A0DOA or =E2=88=A0DOC)</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Note: </strong>In the above figure,</p>
<ul>
<li>DC =3D AB =3D b</li>
<li>AD =3D BC =3D a</li>
<li>=E2=88=A0DAB =3D =E2=88=A0DCB</li>
<li>=E2=88=A0ADC =3D =E2=88=A0ABC</li>
<li>O is the intersecting point of the diagonals</li>
<li>=E2=88=A0DOA =3D =E2=88=A0COB</li>
<li>=E2=88=A0DOC =3D =E2=88=A0AOB</li>
</ul>
<h2>Area of Parallelogram in Vector Form</h2>
<p>If the sides of a parallelogram are given in vector form, then the area =
of the parallelogram can be calculated using its diagonals. Suppose vector =
=E2=80=98a=E2=80=99 and vector =E2=80=98b=E2=80=99 are the two sides of a p=
arallelogram, such that the resulting vector is the diagonal of the paralle=
logram.</p>
<p>Area of a parallelogram in vector form =3D Mod of cross-product of vecto=
r a and vector b</p>
<p><strong>A =3D | a&nbsp;=C3=97 b|</strong></p>
<p>Now, we have to find the area of a parallelogram with respect to diagona=
ls, say d<sub>1</sub> and d<sub>2</sub>,&nbsp; in vector form.</p>
<p>So, we can write;</p>
<p>a + b =3D d<sub>1</sub></p>
<p>b + (-a) =3D d<sub>2</sub></p>
<p>or</p>
<p>b =E2=80=93 a =3D d<sub>2</sub></p>
<p>Thus,</p>
<p>d<sub>1</sub>&nbsp;=C3=97 d<sub>2</sub> =3D (a + b)&nbsp;=C3=97 (b =E2=
=80=93 a)</p>
<p>=3D a&nbsp;=C3=97 (b =E2=80=93 a) + b&nbsp;=C3=97 (b =E2=80=93 a)</p>
<p>=3D a&nbsp;=C3=97 b =E2=80=93 a&nbsp;=C3=97 a + b&nbsp;=C3=97 b =E2=80=
=93 b&nbsp;=C3=97 a</p>
<p>=3D a&nbsp;=C3=97 b =E2=80=93 0 + 0 =E2=80=93 b&nbsp;=C3=97 a</p>
<p>=3D&nbsp;a&nbsp;=C3=97 b =E2=80=93 b&nbsp;=C3=97 a</p>
<p>Since,</p>
<p>a&nbsp;=C3=97 b =3D =E2=80=93 b&nbsp;=C3=97 a</p>
<p>Therefore,</p>
<p>d<sub>1</sub>&nbsp;=C3=97 d<sub>2</sub> =3D&nbsp;a&nbsp;=C3=97 b + a =C3=
=97 b =3D 2 (a =C3=97 b)</p>
<p>a =C3=97 b =3D 1/2 (d<sub>1</sub>&nbsp;=C3=97 d<sub>2</sub>)</p>
<p>Hence,</p>
<p>Area of the parallelogram, when diagonals are given in the vector form b=
ecomes:</p>
<p><strong>A =3D&nbsp;1/2 (d<sub>1</sub>&nbsp;=C3=97 d<sub>2</sub>)</strong=
></p>
<p>where d1 and d2 are vectors of diagonals.</p>
<p><strong>Example: Find the area of a parallelogram whose adjacent sides a=
re given in vectors.</strong></p>
<p>A =3D 3i + 2j and B =3D -3i + 1j</p>
<p>Area of parallelogram =3D |A&nbsp;=C3=97 B|</p>
<div class=3D"mathjax-scroll">\(\begin{array}{l}=3D \begin{vmatrix} i &amp;=
 j &amp; k\\ 3 &amp; 2 &amp; 0\\ -3 &amp; 1 &amp; 0 \end{vmatrix}\end{array=
} \)</div>
<p>=3D i (0-0) =E2=80=93 (0-0) + k(3+6)&nbsp; [Using <a href=3D"https://byj=
us.com/maths/determinant-of-a-3x3-matrix/">determinant of 3 x 3 matrix form=
ula</a>]
</p><p>=3D 9k</p>
<p>Thus, the area of the parallelogram formed by two vectors A and B is equ=
al to 9k sq.unit.</p>
